\cf0 Part 1a: Understanding the data\
Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}How many unique countries are there in each dataset?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	There are 216 unique countries in disasters, 250 in population, and 225 in temp_change datasets.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}For each of the three datasets, are there missing values? If so, which columns have them?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 	All three data sets have missing values. Disasters has missing data in the ISO2 column and year columns from 1980-2024, population is missing values in the Code column, and temp_change is missing data in ISO2 and all year columns from 1961-2024.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Part 2: Global mean temperature over time\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic Global Mean Temperature Anomaly Over Time.png \width14400 \height8640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What does the rolling average do to our data?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The rolling average smooths out our short-term year to year noise in the graph, making the long term increasing trend easier to see. Individual years can spike up or down due to certain events, but the moving average filters that out.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls5\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Which decade (70s, 80s, 90s, 2000s, 2010s) saw the largest jump in average temperature, when compared to the average temperature of the previous decade?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The 2000s saw the largest jump compared to the 90s.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls6\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What other trends do you observe?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 One trend I\'92m noticing is that the most recent years show a massive spike well above the 2010s trend showing further upwards acceleration. Another trend I see is that the 1960s and 1970s were relatively flat compared to the following decades showing the temperatures were close to the 1951-1980 baseline.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Part 3: Temperatures and disasters\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic Temperature vs Disasters-1.png \width14400 \height8640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls7\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Do periods of higher temperature coincide with an increase in disaster frequency?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Yes, both graphs rise together from 1980 to the mid 2000s. However,  disaster counts level off towards roughly after 2000 while temperatures keep rising so the relationship might not be entirely correlated.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls8\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What alternative measures (instead of the number of disasters) could provide more insight?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Some other measures like economic damage, number of people affected, and disaster severity could help provide more insight.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls9\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}How might these other measures change your interpretation?\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 We currently count a massive hurricane the same as a minor flood. Having insight on how many people affected/damages caused by the disaster could give a clearer picture.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sb280\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
