\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls10\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Which continent(s) show the strongest warming trend?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Europe shows the strongest warming trend with Asia following behind.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls11\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Do those same continent(s) experience more disasters?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 No, even with the strongest warming trend, Europe ranks fourth in total disaster count. Asia experiences the most climate-related disasters, followed by North America and Africa, suggesting that disaster frequency depends not just on the factor of temperature.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Part 5: Correlation by chance?\
Interpret the results of the Mann-Kendall test and answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls12\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What does the trend test say for each of the two series above (increasing, decreasing, or no trend)?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The global mean temperature anomaly and total disasters per year show a statistically significant increasing trend with our Mann-Kendall tests: p = 1.2e-14 for temperature and p = 2.6e-10 for disasters.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls13\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What does this tell you about which variable fluctuates more relative to its average?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Temperature CV = 0.6 and disaster CV = 0.35 meaning temperature anomaly fluctuates more relative to its mean. This is because temperature started near zero and rose steeply, while disaster counts started higher and tapered off.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
Part 6: Polynomial regression\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic Polynomial Regression.png \width14400 \height8640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls14\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Which degree best captures the overall disaster occurrence trend?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Degree 10 best captures the trend as it has the greatest R^2 value and is therefore most accurate. Note that having the highest R^2 value doesn\'92t necessarily mean it will predict the future data most accurately.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls15\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What happens to the curve shape as the degree increases?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 As degree increases, the curve shape fits the data more accurately and gets more curvy.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls16\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Why might higher-degree models give misleading confidence about future predictions?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Higher degree polynomials might overfit the data giving a high R^2 value but then not actually being able to predict data outside of the training data range.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls17\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Use the regression model that best fits your data (based on R\super 2 \nosupersub and visual inspection) to predict the global average temperature anomaly for the year 2030.\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 I used the degree 10 model as it has the highest R^2 value and it predicts a 3.56 degrees Celsius. This seems very high and might be a result of overfitting with the degree 10 polynomial.\
\
Part 7: More cheese, more people\
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic Cheese vs Population.png \width14400 \height8640 \appleattachmentpadding0 \appleembedtype0 \appleaqc
}洞\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\qc\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Answer the following questions:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls18\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Which country showed the strongest correlation, and what was the coefficient?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Fiji showed the strongest correlation with US cheese consumption as it had a Pearson coefficient of r = 0.996.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls19\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}Does this imply that U.S. cheese consumption caused population change in that country? Why or why not?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 No this does not imply causation as there is no way in which American cheese consumption would cause Fiji\'92s population to change.  They both just happen to match pretty well by pure chance.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls20\ilvl0\cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}What might explain why some random time series appear correlated even when unrelated?\
\pard\tx720\pardeftab720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Any pair of increasing variables over time is bound to show a strong positive Pearson coefficient simply because they share a similar trend in the same time period. This can happen even if totally unrelated.\
